= GPU.sb3 =

GPU.sb3 is an extension that allows you to run [[WebGPU]] compute shaders from your Scratch projects, enabling massively parallel computation on the GPU.

; Extension ID : <code>gpusb3</code>
; Author : derpygamer2142
; License : MIT
; Requires : Unsandboxed execution

== Overview ==

GPU.sb3 exposes a full WebGPU compute shader pipeline directly to Scratch blocks. You can:

* Allocate GPU buffers and textures
* Upload data from JavaScript ArrayBuffers to the GPU
* Write compute shaders using WGSL blocks
* Run shaders with configurable dispatch dimensions
* Read results back to ArrayBuffer views

The extension requires WebGPU support in the browser. As of 2024, WebGPU is available in Chrome/Edge 113+ and experimentally in Firefox and Safari. It also requires running unsandboxed.

=== Required setup ===

Before using any GPU.sb3 blocks you must either:

* Add '''Reconnect to GPU''' to your project's startup (the extension calls this automatically when loaded, but reconnecting after page load may be needed), or
* Use the '''WebGPU available?''' and '''Connected to GPU?''' booleans to check readiness before executing shaders.

=== Typical workflow ===

# '''Reconnect to GPU''' — acquire device
# Create '''bind group layout''' and its '''entries''' — describe what the GPU receives
# Create '''buffers''' / '''textures''' — allocate GPU memory
# Create '''bind group''' — bind resources to bindings
# Define '''shader''' hat with WGSL blocks inside — write shader code
# '''compile shaders''' — turn blocks into WGSL and compile
# Write CPU data — use ArrayBuffer blocks, then '''Write [SIZE] elements … to buffer'''
# '''Run shader''' — dispatch workgroups
# Copy output buffer to a MAP_READ buffer, '''Read buffer''' — retrieve results
# Read data out of an ArrayBuffer '''view'''

== Block reference ==

=== GPU management ===

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>WebGPU available?</code> || Boolean || Returns <code>true</code> if the browser supports WebGPU (<code>navigator.gpu</code> exists).
|-
| <code>Connected to GPU?</code> || Boolean || Returns <code>true</code> if the extension has successfully acquired a WebGPU device.
|-
| <code>Reconnect to GPU</code> || Command || Releases all existing resources and reinitialises the WebGPU adapter and device. Run this at the start of your project to ensure a clean state.
|-
| <code>compile shaders</code> || Command || Traverses all '''Define shader''' hat blocks and compiles them into WGSL shader modules. Must be called before '''Run shader'''.
|-
| <code>Run shader [GPUFUNC] using bind group [BINDGROUP] dimensions x: [X] y: [Y] z: [Z]</code> || Command || Dispatches a compiled shader. <code>GPUFUNC</code> is the shader name from its hat block; <code>BINDGROUP</code> is the bind group to use. X/Y/Z are the workgroup dispatch counts.
|}

=== Error handling ===

GPU.sb3 catches GPU errors and exposes them to the project rather than throwing unhandled exceptions.

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>when error thrown</code> || Hat (event) || Triggered whenever the extension catches an error. Use this to handle GPU errors gracefully.
|-
| <code>Error</code> || Reporter || Returns the current error object as a JSON string. Fields: <code>name</code>, <code>body</code>, <code>source</code>, <code>full</code>.
|-
| <code>clear current error</code> || Command || Clears the stored error so subsequent checks start fresh.
|}

Example error object:
<syntaxhighlight lang="json">
{
  "name": "DeviceLost",
  "body": "Device was lost.",
  "source": "wgpu",
  "full": { ... }
}
</syntaxhighlight>

=== Shader definition (hat) ===

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>Define shader [NAME] using bind group layout [BGL]</code> || Hat (event) || All WGSL blocks placed under this hat become the body of shader <code>NAME</code>. <code>BGL</code> must match the name of a bind group layout created with '''Create bind group layout'''. Multiple hats can be active at the same time.
|}

== Data input blocks ==

These blocks manage the GPU-side resources that shaders read from and write to.

=== Bind group layouts ===

A '''bind group layout''' describes the types and bindings that a shader expects. It must be created before the bind group or shader that uses it.

Bind group layout blocks use an orange/gold colour.

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>Create bind group layout called [NAME]</code> || Conditional (C‑shape) || Opens a scope. Place '''Add bind group layout entry''' blocks inside. When the scope ends, the layout named <code>NAME</code> is registered.
|-
| <code>Add bind group layout entry with binding [BINDING] for type [TYPE] and descriptor [DESC]</code> || Command || Adds one binding entry to the enclosing layout. <code>BINDING</code> is the slot index (0, 1, 2…). <code>TYPE</code> is from the [[#BGLENTRYTYPES|BGLENTRYTYPES menu]] (<code>buffer</code> or <code>storageTexture</code>). <code>DESC</code> is a descriptor reporter (see below).
|-
| <code>Buffer layout entry descriptor with usage type [TYPE]</code> || Reporter || Produces a descriptor for a buffer entry. <code>TYPE</code> is from the [[#BUFFERENTRYTYPE|BUFFERENTRYTYPE menu]]: <code>read-only-storage</code>, <code>storage</code>, or <code>uniform</code>.
|-
| <code>Texture layout entry descriptor with usage type [TYPE] and format [FORMAT]</code> || Reporter || Produces a descriptor for a storage texture entry. <code>TYPE</code> is <code>write-only</code>, <code>read-only</code>, or <code>read-write</code>. <code>FORMAT</code> is from the [[#TEXTURECOLORFORMATS|texture format menu]].
|}

=== Bind groups ===

A '''bind group''' pairs actual resources (buffers, textures) with the bindings described by a layout.

Bind group blocks use a reddish-orange colour.

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>Create bind group called [NAME] using layout [LAYOUT]</code> || Conditional (C‑shape) || Opens a scope. Place '''Add bind group entry''' blocks inside. <code>LAYOUT</code> must match an existing bind group layout name.
|-
| <code>Add bind group entry with binding [BINDING] of type [TYPE] using resource named [RESOURCE]</code> || Command || Binds a named resource to a slot inside the enclosing bind group. <code>TYPE</code> is <code>buffer</code> or <code>storageTexture</code>.
|-
| <code>Usage [A] | [B]</code> || Reporter || Performs a bitwise OR of two usage flags. Use this to combine multiple [[#BUFFERUSAGE|buffer usage]] flags (e.g. <code>STORAGE | COPY_SRC</code>).
|}

=== GPU buffers ===

A '''GPU buffer''' is a block of GPU memory. It is distinct from a JavaScript ArrayBuffer.

Buffer blocks use a maroon colour.

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>Create buffer called [NAME] with size(in bytes) [SIZE] and usage flags [USAGE]</code> || Command || Allocates a GPUBuffer. <code>SIZE</code> must be a multiple of 4. <code>USAGE</code> is a combination of [[#BUFFERUSAGE|buffer usage flags]].
|-
| <code>Buffer usage [USAGE]</code> || Reporter || Returns the numeric constant for a named usage flag. Combine multiple flags with the '''Usage A | B''' block.
|-
| <code>Write [SIZE] elements of data from arraybuffer [ARRAY] to buffer [BUFFER] from offset [OFF1] to offset [OFF2]</code> || Command || Copies data from a CPU-side ArrayBuffer (or view) to a GPU buffer. <code>OFF1</code> is the byte offset into the GPU buffer; <code>OFF2</code> is the element offset into the ArrayBuffer view.
|-
| <code>Copy [NUMBYTES] bytes of data from buffer [BUF1] from position [BUF1OFF] to buffer [BUF2] at position [BUF2OFF]</code> || Command || GPU-side buffer copy. Offsets are '''in bytes'''. Commonly used to copy from a <code>STORAGE</code> buffer into a <code>MAP_READ</code> buffer before reading back results.
|-
| <code>Read buffer [BUFFER] to arraybuffer [ARRAYBUFFER]</code> || Command || Maps a <code>MAP_READ</code> buffer and copies its contents into a CPU-side ArrayBuffer. The buffer must have been created with the <code>MAP_READ</code> usage flag.
|-
| <code>Copy texture [TEXTURE] to buffer [BUFFER] with dimensions [WIDTH] [HEIGHT]</code> || Command || Reads the pixels of a GPU texture into a GPU buffer.
|}

=== GPU textures ===

Texture blocks use a sky-blue colour.

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>Create texture called [NAME] width dimensions [WIDTH] [HEIGHT], color format [FORMAT] and usage [USAGE]</code> || Command || Allocates a 2D GPUTexture. <code>FORMAT</code> is from the [[#TEXTURECOLORFORMATS|texture format menu]]. <code>USAGE</code> is a combination of texture usage flags.
|-
| <code>Texture usage [USAGE]</code> || Reporter || Returns the numeric constant for a named texture usage flag.
|-
| <code>Copy elements with dimensions [WIDTH], [HEIGHT] from offset [OFFSET] in buffer [BUFFER] to texture [TEXTURE]</code> || Command || Copies pixel data from a GPU buffer into a GPU texture. <code>OFFSET</code> is in bytes.
|-
| <code>Write texture data from [IMAGE] to texture [TEXTURE]</code> || Command || Copies a project costume's pixel data directly into a GPU texture. The costume is selected from the [[#IMAGELIST|image list menu]].
|}

=== Buffer and texture usage flags ===

==== Buffer usage flags <span id="BUFFERUSAGE"></span> ====

{| class="wikitable"
! Flag !! Value !! Notes
|-
| <code>MAP_READ</code> || 1 || Allows mapping the buffer for CPU reads. Required for '''Read buffer'''.
|-
| <code>MAP_WRITE</code> || 2 || Allows mapping the buffer for CPU writes.
|-
| <code>COPY_SRC</code> || 4 || Source of a copy operation.
|-
| <code>COPY_DST</code> || 8 || Destination of a copy or write operation.
|-
| <code>INDEX</code> || 16 || Index buffer (not used in compute).
|-
| <code>VERTEX</code> || 32 || Vertex buffer (not used in compute).
|-
| <code>UNIFORM</code> || 64 || Uniform buffer.
|-
| <code>STORAGE</code> || 128 || Storage buffer (read/write in shaders).
|-
| <code>QUERY_RESOLVE</code> || 256 || For resolving query sets.
|}

The most common combination for a read-back workflow is <code>STORAGE | COPY_SRC</code> (128 | 4 = 132) for the shader output buffer, and <code>MAP_READ | COPY_DST</code> (1 | 8 = 9) for the staging buffer.

==== Texture usage flags ====

{| class="wikitable"
! Flag !! Notes
|-
| <code>COPY_SRC</code> || Source of a texture copy.
|-
| <code>COPY_DST</code> || Destination of a texture write.
|-
| <code>TEXTURE_BINDING</code> || Allows the texture to be bound as a sampled texture (read in shaders).
|-
| <code>STORAGE_BINDING</code> || Allows the texture to be bound as a storage texture (read/write in compute shaders).
|}

== ArrayBuffer blocks ==

ArrayBuffers are CPU-side memory that you use to prepare data for upload to the GPU and to read results back. They are standard JavaScript <code>ArrayBuffer</code> objects wrapped in typed-array views.

ArrayBuffer blocks use a red colour.

=== Buffer management ===

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>List arraybuffers</code> || Reporter || Returns a JSON array of the names of all currently allocated ArrayBuffers.
|-
| <code>Create arraybuffer called [ARRAYBUFFER] with length [LENGTH]</code> || Command || Creates a new zeroed ArrayBuffer with the given byte length.
|-
| <code>Create arraybuffer and view called [ARRAYBUFFER] from array [ARRAY] of type [TYPE]</code> || Command || Creates both an ArrayBuffer and an initial typed-array view from a JSON array (e.g. <code>[1,2,3]</code>). <code>TYPE</code> is from the [[#TYPEDARRAYTYPES|typed array types menu]].
|-
| <code>Delete arraybuffer [ARRAYBUFFER]</code> || Command || Frees the named ArrayBuffer and any views that reference it.
|-
| <code>Resize arraybuffer [ARRAYBUFFER] to [SIZE] bytes</code> || Command || Resizes an existing ArrayBuffer. Existing data may be truncated or padded with zeros.
|}

=== View management ===

A '''view''' is a typed-array window into an ArrayBuffer that lets you read and write individual elements at a specific numeric type.

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>List views</code> || Reporter || Returns a JSON array of the names of all currently allocated views.
|-
| <code>View arraybuffer [ARRAYBUFFER] as [TYPE] called [NAME]</code> || Command || Creates a typed-array view over an ArrayBuffer. <code>TYPE</code> is from the [[#TYPEDARRAYTYPES|typed array types menu]].
|-
| <code>Delete view [NAME]</code> || Command || Removes the named view.
|}

=== View data operations ===

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>Set item [INDEX] of view [VIEW] to [VALUE]</code> || Command || Sets a single element of the view at the given index.
|-
| <code>Copy data from array [ARRAY] to view [VIEW] from index [INDEX]</code> || Command || Sets multiple elements of a view from a JSON array, starting at <code>INDEX</code>.
|-
| <code>Fill items [START] to [END] of view [VIEW] with [VALUE]</code> || Command || Sets every element between <code>START</code> and <code>END</code> (exclusive) to <code>VALUE</code>.
|-
| <code>Item [INDEX] of arraybuffer view [VIEW]</code> || Reporter || Returns a single element from the view.
|-
| <code>Items [START] to [END] of view [VIEW]</code> || Reporter || Returns a JSON array containing the elements from index <code>START</code> to <code>END</code> (exclusive).
|-
| <code>Get view [VIEW] as array</code> || Reporter || Returns the entire view as a JSON array.
|-
| <code>[PROP] of view [VIEW]</code> || Reporter || Returns a property of the typed array. Options: <code>BYTES_PER_ELEMENT</code>, <code>byteLength</code>, <code>length</code>.
|}

