== WGSL blocks ==

WGSL (WebGPU Shading Language) blocks let you construct compute shaders using Scratch-style programming. They are placed inside '''Define shader''' hat blocks and are compiled into real WGSL source code by '''compile shaders'''.

For full WGSL language documentation see:
* [https://www.w3.org/TR/WGSL/ WGSL Specification]
* [https://google.github.io/tour-of-wgsl/ Tour of WGSL]

=== Variables <span id="variables"></span> ===

Variable blocks use a yellow colour.

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>declare [VARTYPE] variable as [NAME] with value [VALUE]: [TYPE]</code> || Command || Declares a local variable. <code>VARTYPE</code> is <code>var</code>, <code>let</code>, or <code>const</code>. <code>TYPE</code> is the WGSL type (or <code>auto</code> to infer). Leave <code>VALUE</code> empty to declare without initialising.
|-
| <code>Bind shader resource # [BINDNUM] to variable [VARNAME] with settings [SETTINGS] type [INPUTTYPE]</code> || Command || Emits a <code>@group(0) @binding(...) var&lt;...&gt;</code> declaration. <code>SETTINGS</code> is the variable's address space and access mode (e.g. <code>storage, read_write</code>). <code>INPUTTYPE</code> is the WGSL type (e.g. <code>array&lt;f32&gt;</code>). Leave <code>SETTINGS</code> empty for textures and samplers.
|-
| <code>Variable usage [USAGE] next [NEXT]</code> || Reporter || Builds a comma-separated access mode/address space string for use in <code>Bind shader resource</code>. Chain multiple with the <code>NEXT</code> input.
|-
| <code>Variable [VARNAME] [VAROP] [INPUT]</code> || Command || Emits a variable assignment statement such as <code>x += 1;</code>. <code>VAROP</code> options: <code>=</code>, <code>+=</code>, <code>-=</code>, <code>*=</code>, <code>/=</code>, <code>%=</code>, <code>&=</code>, <code>|=</code>, <code>^=</code>, <code>>>=</code>, <code><<=</code>.
|-
| <code>Get variable [NAME]</code> || Reporter || Emits the variable name as a WGSL expression.
|-
| <code>Pointer to variable [VAR]</code> || Reporter || Emits <code>&amp;VAR</code> — a pointer to the variable. Required by some atomic functions.
|}

=== Types ===

Type blocks use a dark-cyan colour.

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>Base type [TYPE]</code> || Reporter || Returns a primitive WGSL type: <code>i32</code>, <code>u32</code>, <code>f32</code>, or <code>bool</code>.
|-
| <code>Create type [TYPE] of [SUBTYPE], length(array only!) [LENGTH]</code> || Reporter || Constructs a parametric type such as <code>vec3&lt;f32&gt;</code> or <code>array&lt;f32, 10&gt;</code>. <code>TYPE</code> is <code>vec2</code>, <code>vec3</code>, <code>vec4</code>, or <code>array</code>.
|-
| <code>Matrix type with [COLUMNS] columns and [ROWS] rows</code> || Reporter || Returns a matrix type like <code>mat2x3</code>.
|-
| <code>Texture type of [TYPE] with access [ACCESS]</code> || Reporter || Returns <code>texture_storage_2d&lt;FORMAT, ACCESS&gt;</code>. Used in '''Bind shader resource''' for storage textures.
|-
| <code>Type of struct [STRUCT]</code> || Reporter || Returns the name of a struct type so it can be used as a type in variable declarations.
|-
| <code>Create atomic of type [BASE]</code> || Reporter || Returns <code>atomic&lt;i32&gt;</code> or <code>atomic&lt;u32&gt;</code>. Use as a type in variable declarations.
|}

=== Objects and structs ===

Object blocks use a dark-green colour.

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>Construct type [TYPE] with values [VALUES]</code> || Reporter || Emits a constructor call such as <code>f32(1.5)</code> or <code>vec3&lt;f32&gt;(1.0, 2.0, 3.0)</code>. <code>VALUES</code> is a comma-separated argument string.
|-
| <code>Declare struct called [NAME]</code> || Conditional (C‑shape) || Opens a struct declaration scope. Place '''Add property''' blocks inside.
|-
| <code>Add property called [PROPERTY] with type [TYPE] to struct</code> || Command || Adds a field to the enclosing struct.
|-
| <code>In object [ARRAY] get index [INDEX]</code> || Reporter || Emits <code>ARRAY[INDEX]</code> — array/vector element access.
|-
| <code>In object [OBJECT] get property [PROP]</code> || Reporter || Emits <code>OBJECT.PROP</code> — struct/swizzle access.
|}

=== Compute shader entry point ===

Control-flow blocks use a light-brown colour.

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>Computer shader with workgroup size [WGSIZE]</code> || Conditional (C‑shape) || Emits the <code>@compute @workgroup_size(...) fn computeShader(...)</code> entry point. <code>WGSIZE</code> is a JSON array such as <code>[64]</code> or <code>[8,8]</code>. Place all shader logic inside. The built-in variables <code>workgroup_id</code>, <code>local_invocation_id</code>, <code>global_invocation_id</code>, <code>local_invocation_index</code>, and <code>num_workgroups</code> are automatically provided.
|}

=== Control flow ===

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>For [VARNAME] in range [START], [END]</code> || Conditional (C‑shape) || Emits a <code>loop</code> that increments <code>VARNAME</code> from <code>START</code> to <code>END</code>.
|-
| <code>While [COND]</code> || Conditional (C‑shape) || Emits a <code>while (COND) { ... }</code> loop. Place blocks inside for the loop body.
|-
| <code>break</code> || Command (terminal) || Emits a <code>break;</code> statement.
|-
| <code>continue</code> || Command (terminal) || Emits a <code>continue;</code> statement.
|}

The '''For''' and '''While''' blocks are implemented as CONDITIONAL blocks (C‑shapes). Any Scratch <code>if</code> or <code>if‑else</code> block placed inside a shader hat is also compiled to WGSL.

=== Functions ===

Function blocks use a purple colour.

{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%"
! Block !! Type !! Description
|-
| <code>WGSL builtin [OPERATION] with args [VALUE]</code> || Reporter || Calls a WGSL built-in function. <code>VALUE</code> can be a single value or a '''Func arg input''' chain. See [[#WGSLFUNCS|built-in function list]] below.
|-
| <code>Func arg input [ARG], next [NEXT]</code> || Reporter || Builds a comma-separated argument list. Nest multiples in the <code>NEXT</code> input to pass more than one argument.
|-
| <code>Def function [FUNCNAME] that returns type [TYPE] with args [ARGS]</code> || Conditional (C‑shape) || Declares a WGSL function. <code>TYPE</code> is the return type (<code>void</code> returns nothing). Place '''Def arg''' blocks in <code>ARGS</code> to define parameters.
|-
| <code>Def arg [ARGNAME]: [ARGTYPE], next [NEXTARG]</code> || Reporter || Declares one parameter of a function. Chain multiple with <code>NEXTARG</code>.
|-
| <code>Get function arg [ARGNAME]</code> || Reporter || Emits the name of a function parameter so it can be used in the function body.
|-
| <code>Return [TORETURN]</code> || Command (terminal) || Emits a <code>return TORETURN;</code> statement.
|-
| <code>Run function [FUNCNAME] with args [ARGS]</code> (command) || Command || Calls a function and discards the return value.
|-
| <code>Run function [FUNCNAME] with args [ARGS]</code> (reporter) || Reporter || Calls a function and uses its return value as an expression.
|}

